# Pitfalls — Infinite Scroll vs Pagination

The most common mistakes developers make when implementing either pattern.

---

## Pitfall 1: Using `OFFSET` for Infinite Scroll

**What developers do:**

```php
// ❌ This breaks at scale and produces duplicate/missing items
$page = $request->integer('page', 1);
$products = Product::orderByDesc('created_at')
    ->skip(($page - 1) * 20)
    ->take(20)
    ->get();
```

**Why it fails:**
- At `OFFSET 10000`, PostgreSQL reads and discards 10,000 rows on every request
- If a new product is inserted between page loads, every user sees a duplicate on the next page or skips an item
- Infinite scroll with offset is the worst of both worlds — slow queries AND incorrect results

**Fix:**

```php
// ✅ Cursor-based — fast at any depth, no duplicates
if ($cursor) {
    $decoded = json_decode(base64_decode($cursor), true);
    $query->where(function ($q) use ($decoded) {
        $q->where('created_at', '<', $decoded['created_at'])
          ->orWhere(fn($q2) => $q2
              ->where('created_at', $decoded['created_at'])
              ->where('id', '<', $decoded['id'])
          );
    });
}
```

