## Pitfall 2: Attaching Scroll Listeners Directly

**What developers do:**

```js
// ❌ This runs on every single scroll event — hundreds of times per second
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
  const nearBottom =
    window.scrollY + window.innerHeight >= document.body.scrollHeight - 100;
  if (nearBottom && !loading) {
    loadMore();
  }
});
```

**Why it fails:**
- Scroll events fire continuously, causing massive CPU usage
- Even with debounce, this is fragile and can fire multiple times
- The scroll position arithmetic breaks inside scrollable containers (not `window`)

**Fix:**

```js
// ✅ IntersectionObserver — browser-native, zero scroll event overhead
const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
  ([entry]) => {
    if (entry.isIntersecting && hasNextPage) fetchNextPage();
  },
  { rootMargin: '200px' }
);
observer.observe(sentinelRef.current);
```

